properties.description:
STAY INFORMED - Carnarvon Gorge National Park - fire as at  3:12pm Monday, 20 November 2023 

 


Warning level: ADVICE


 


Warning area: Carnarvon Gorge, Buckland, Consuelo, Rewan, Mount Drummond, Mount Owen, and Springsure


 

The fire burning in Carnarvon National Park and Bandana State Forest could burn for several weeks. ‎

 

‎


 

What you should do:

- Stay informed because conditions could change:

- Check the QFES Current Bushfires and Warnings website regularly.

- Follow QFES on Facebook and Twitter.

- Listen to your local radio station.

- Check your bushfire survival plan. If you do not have one, make one on the QFES website.

- Keep medications close by.

- Avoid smoke – stay indoors, close windows and doors, and avoid driving through smoke.

- Check on neighbours, friends and family in the area if you can.

- Watch out for firefighters still working in the area.

- Do not fly drones around the fire. Drones affect air operations.

- If your life or property is in danger, call Triple Zero (000) immediately.



 

Impacts:

- No properties are at risk.

- Smoke can make it hard for some people to breathe.

- Smoke can make it hard to see when you are driving.

- Some roads may be closed.



 

Further Information:

- For all warnings, visit the QFES Current Bushfires and Warnings website.

- Follow QFES on Facebook and Twitter.

- For road closures, visit the QLD Traffic website or call 13 19 40.

- Visit the Department of Environment and Science website for live air quality data.

- Find out how to get ready for a bushfire on the QFES website under Prepare - Bushfire.

- Natural disasters can affect your mental health. If you need help contact:

- Lifeline website or call 13 11 14.

- Beyond Blue website or call 1300 224 636.

- Kids Helpline website or call 1800 551 800.



 

This fire is expected to keep burning for several weeks. Updates will be provided only when the situation changes.

 

This warning is from Queensland Fire and Emergency Services.

properties.description:
RETURN WITH CAUTION - The Pines (near Millmerran) - fire as at  1:33pm Monday, 20 November 2023

Warning level:  ADVICE

Warning area:  Properties between Rosella Avenue, Pine Ridge Road, Thyme Avenue, Scrubby Creek Boondanilla Road to the Gore Highway 

The fire near Flamingo Road is now burning in containment lines and will continue to burn for several days. It is travelling towards The Pines. Firefighters are on site.

If you left the area, you can return with caution.


 

What you should do:


- Be careful around damaged buildings.

- Watch out for burnt trees, hot embers on the ground and fallen powerlines.

- Stay away from damaged buildings, trees, parks and other public places.

- Wear strong boots and protective clothing.

- Stay informed:

- Keep checking the QFES Current Bushfires and Warnings website

- Follow QFES on Facebook and Twitter

- Listen to your local radio station

- Check on neighbours and help if it is safe.

- Keep important medication with you.

- Watch out for firefighters still working in the area.

- Do not fly drones around the fire. Drones affect air operations.



 

Impacts: 


- Fire conditions have eased but the situation could change quickly.

- There has been some damage in the area.

- No properties are in danger at this time.

- Some roads could be closed because of fallen trees, branches or powerlines.

- Some places have no power.

- Mobile phone and internet services might not work.

- The ground in burnt areas could still be very hot.

- Smoke may stay in the area for several days.

- Smoke can make it hard for some people to breathe.


Support and recovery help:

- There is a place of refuge at Wylahra Grove Progress Recreation Hall at 72 Primrose Drive Millmerran Downs, Queensland 4357.

- Go to the Ergon Energy website (www.ergon.com.au) for power outage information.

- Natural disasters can affect your mental health. If you need help contact:

- Lifeline website (www.lifeline.org.au) or call 13 11 14.

- Beyond Blue website (www.beyondblue.org.au) or call 1300 224 636.

- Kids Helpline website (www.kidshelpline.com.au) or call 1800 551 800.



 

Further Information: 


- Visit the Department of Environment and Science website for live air quality data.

- For road closures, visit the QLD Traffic website or call 13 19 40.



 


Next update will be issued when the situation changes.

 

This warning is from Queensland Fire and Emergency Services.
